WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:09.960
Over the past two years, we've been working on this workflow that's been helpful for us

00:00:09.960 --> 00:00:14.120
in processing large amounts of data very quickly in order to create products that help guide

00:00:14.120 --> 00:00:18.000
the decision-making in the state of where to allocate resources. This workflow involves

00:00:18.000 --> 00:00:22.840
three main products, Microsoft Azure DevOps, RStudio Workbench, and RStudio Connect. If

00:00:22.840 --> 00:00:26.080
you were at the keynote this morning, you'll realize some of these terms are a little outdated

00:00:26.080 --> 00:00:33.160
since RStudio is now changing to Posit. When I first started working at CDPH, it was December

00:00:33.160 --> 00:00:37.279
2020. I was living in Washington, D.C. in Foggy Bottoms, not too far from here. If you

00:00:37.279 --> 00:00:41.040
remember in our personal lives, it was quite stressful, so going outside was kind of like

00:00:41.040 --> 00:00:45.000
rolling the dice of whether you might get sick or get others sick. And you can imagine

00:00:45.000 --> 00:00:49.119
working in public health is also quite stressful. Our infrastructure wasn't prepared for the

00:00:49.119 --> 00:00:52.880
amount of data that COVID was going to provide, and we were often trying to catch up and get

00:00:52.880 --> 00:00:57.200
ahead. I happened to be working on a report at that time that got sent out at the end

00:00:57.200 --> 00:01:02.480
of the day, and I would get this beautiful data set that was processed by my many colleagues

00:01:02.480 --> 00:01:06.000
from the local health jurisdictions and at the state level, and sometimes there would

00:01:06.000 --> 00:01:10.199
be delays. It's no fault that anyone, the situation was very complicated, data was always

00:01:10.199 --> 00:01:16.919
changing, so this often meant 9 p.m., 10 p.m., 11 p.m., California time, midnight, 1 a.m.,

00:01:16.919 --> 00:01:21.320
2 a.m. in D.C. So I often looked like this. I was very tired, and my cat was wondering

00:01:21.320 --> 00:01:26.199
why I'm still awake. As a team, we knew this wasn't feasible, and we needed to do something

00:01:26.199 --> 00:01:30.199
to change this, not only to meet the needs of the state, but also to improve our work-life

00:01:30.199 --> 00:01:36.000
balance. So eventually this workflow came about, allowing us to do our work more efficiently,

00:01:36.000 --> 00:01:41.480
and I got into bed at a more reasonable time. So reducing our stress required four main

00:01:41.480 --> 00:01:46.360
things. The first one is how we prioritize our task. How do we improve our ability to

00:01:46.360 --> 00:01:51.599
collaborate with each other? How do we decrease our turnaround time? And lastly, how do we

00:01:51.599 --> 00:01:57.760
scale our work? So I'm going to start with how do we improve our prioritization? So during

00:01:57.760 --> 00:02:01.199
this time, there were many requests always coming in, and there was often an undertone

00:02:01.199 --> 00:02:05.720
of I needed this yesterday, and that's very true, because the questions and issues that

00:02:05.720 --> 00:02:10.720
we're having impacted the health of millions of people. And the issue, however, is that

00:02:10.720 --> 00:02:15.720
as a team, we're quite limited. There's only so many of us. Our skills vary, and we want

00:02:15.720 --> 00:02:20.199
to be able to solve these issues, but we only have so much time as well. So we needed

00:02:20.199 --> 00:02:24.759
a way to prioritize how we move forward in our work. So that's where our first product

00:02:24.759 --> 00:02:29.160
comes in, Microsoft Azure DevOps, and we use Microsoft Azure DevOps at CDPH because we're

00:02:29.160 --> 00:02:34.000
a Microsoft shop, but you could use other DevOps platforms as well in place of this.

00:02:34.000 --> 00:02:39.520
So we started using Azure DevOps for project management, in particular a sprint board,

00:02:39.520 --> 00:02:44.119
and a sprint is a defined period of time that you set to complete a number of tasks, and

00:02:44.119 --> 00:02:47.759
what's really great about a sprint is that at the very beginning of the sprint, it forces

00:02:47.759 --> 00:02:53.039
you to sit down and decide what needs to be done, what can realistically be done in this

00:02:53.039 --> 00:02:57.320
time period, and who's going to do it. And for us, we happened to use a two-week sprint

00:02:57.320 --> 00:03:01.080
time, but you could use a different amount of time as well. So what I'm going to do next

00:03:01.080 --> 00:03:05.679
is show you what our sprint board looks like to give you a sense of that. So we have five

00:03:05.679 --> 00:03:12.119
columns, features, not started, declined, in progress, and done. In the feature column,

00:03:12.119 --> 00:03:16.080
you're going to have an overarching project, so, for example, preparing for the conference

00:03:16.080 --> 00:03:19.639
talk, and within that, you're going to have a number of tasks to complete within your

00:03:19.639 --> 00:03:24.759
sprint. So in the not started, I might have a task about drafting slides or practicing

00:03:24.759 --> 00:03:30.320
this presentation, and you can be the judge of whether I successfully did these or not.

00:03:30.320 --> 00:03:35.039
I may have a decline column, such as adding cat gifs, and at some point decided this wasn't

00:03:35.039 --> 00:03:39.600
a professional enough thing to add, so I'm not going to do that. I'll have an in progress

00:03:39.600 --> 00:03:43.520
column, such as drafting outline, which I need to do prior to doing the slides or practicing

00:03:43.520 --> 00:03:47.839
my presentation, and lastly, I'll finish a couple of tasks, too, such as making this

00:03:47.839 --> 00:03:52.639
sprint board example, which, again, you can judge whether I successfully did that or not.

00:03:52.639 --> 00:03:56.160
And then we'll have other rows with other features for separate tasks, and this creates

00:03:56.160 --> 00:04:00.399
a really great visualization for our team of how we're doing in this sprint, and what's

00:04:00.399 --> 00:04:04.639
really powerful is that as sprints continue to occur, we can look back in time and see

00:04:04.639 --> 00:04:08.839
how successful we were at completing our task and modify how we're going to move forward

00:04:08.839 --> 00:04:13.240
in the next sprint. And if you're disappointed that I didn't add any cat gifs, I added some

00:04:13.240 --> 00:04:18.119
last minute for you all. So next, how did we improve our collaboration?

00:04:18.119 --> 00:04:22.600
So when I first started, we were using Git and DevOps principles in some places, but

00:04:22.600 --> 00:04:27.320
it wasn't a main part of our workflow, so a lot of our work was shared across a shared

00:04:27.320 --> 00:04:33.239
drive or folder at work, and that often meant copying your R script, for example, and then

00:04:33.239 --> 00:04:36.920
making edits and later putting it back together, which over time was starting to make a lot

00:04:36.920 --> 00:04:40.200
of problems, especially when it came down to production or it was late at night, at

00:04:40.200 --> 00:04:45.600
midnight, and edits were just very frustrating and tiring to do.

00:04:45.600 --> 00:04:52.679
So we started to use Git workflow more effectively and made it a main part of our workflow.

00:04:52.679 --> 00:04:56.399
So if you think about our work in RStudio Workbench, it's kind of like we're in a silo.

00:04:56.399 --> 00:04:59.880
It's really hard to share this work with others or the colleagues, and we wanted to be able

00:04:59.880 --> 00:05:03.040
to do that. So that's where we started using repositories

00:05:03.040 --> 00:05:08.239
via Azure DevOps, and a repository is a place where you can store your code safely, have

00:05:08.239 --> 00:05:13.519
version control, and it's the central place that all of your work can live, and what's

00:05:13.519 --> 00:05:18.839
great about this is that via RStudio and Git, we can move our work outside of our silo into

00:05:18.839 --> 00:05:23.799
this repository, and in that same vein, I can move other people's work from the repositories

00:05:23.799 --> 00:05:28.559
into my Workbench and work on it there. Now, you can have an entire workshop about

00:05:28.559 --> 00:05:32.720
Git and still may not understand it. It's very confusing, but it's a really great resource

00:05:32.720 --> 00:05:37.359
by Jenny Bryan called Happy Git that's related to using Git and R that I highly encourage

00:05:37.359 --> 00:05:41.079
you to check out if you want to get started with Git and R.

00:05:41.079 --> 00:05:44.839
So you can think of repositories as if you're storing your code safely. So in these photos

00:05:44.839 --> 00:05:50.519
by Edward Muybridge, we're seeing this bird in flight, and we're getting snapshots of

00:05:50.519 --> 00:05:54.399
it over time, and you can think of our code, every time we make a commit or a save, we're

00:05:54.399 --> 00:05:59.959
saving a version of it in memory in a repository. So maybe you want to put this last snapshot

00:05:59.959 --> 00:06:04.399
into production, but something goes wrong. What's great about repositories is that we

00:06:04.399 --> 00:06:08.679
can roll back the clock and use this previous version to go into production and in the meantime

00:06:08.679 --> 00:06:15.440
fix our errors that occurred later on. Another really great feature is that you can

00:06:15.440 --> 00:06:19.079
make what's called a fork or a branch of your repository, and that's like making a copy

00:06:19.079 --> 00:06:22.239
of it, and you can kind of think of it as if you're working in your own lane in that

00:06:22.239 --> 00:06:25.959
sense. We're all running in this sprint, and I have my own fork or branch, and I'm working

00:06:25.959 --> 00:06:29.959
it, making edits, and if I happen to make a mistake, it's not going to affect others

00:06:29.959 --> 00:06:36.119
in their lane. So it gives us a really great opportunity to try new things out, fall over,

00:06:36.119 --> 00:06:41.720
break the app, all of those things that we don't want to happen during production.

00:06:41.720 --> 00:06:45.959
And lastly, how do we improve our turnaround time and scalability? So we're always getting

00:06:45.959 --> 00:06:51.640
requests and lots of data that we're taking ownership of, and these data processing can

00:06:51.640 --> 00:06:55.399
take hours, and at the same time, we also want to be able to scale our work and share

00:06:55.399 --> 00:07:00.320
it with others. So that's where our final product comes in, RStudio Connect, and this

00:07:00.320 --> 00:07:04.040
is a server that allows you to automate your processes, and what's really cool is that

00:07:04.040 --> 00:07:09.480
from our repositories in Azure DevOps, we can deploy our work into RStudio Connect.

00:07:09.480 --> 00:07:15.399
And from Connect, we can automate data processing, we can schedule reports, and we can host Shiny

00:07:15.399 --> 00:07:19.399
apps. So RStudio Connect provided us more processing

00:07:19.399 --> 00:07:23.920
power, which allowed us to do analyses more quickly. So just as an example, this is one

00:07:23.920 --> 00:07:28.839
of our servers. We have about 251 gigabytes of RAM, which is a lot, or another example

00:07:28.839 --> 00:07:33.000
of the amount of CPU cores available, and we have a number of these servers available

00:07:33.000 --> 00:07:38.279
to us to do different types of data processing or host apps, and I can't explain the giddiness

00:07:38.279 --> 00:07:42.200
I felt the first time I ran a script on Connect that took ten minutes when it used to take

00:07:42.200 --> 00:07:46.600
over an hour to run if it didn't crash. So Connect was a really great lifesaver in terms

00:07:46.600 --> 00:07:52.480
of finishing our data processing in a more quick manner, allowing me to go to sleep earlier.

00:07:52.480 --> 00:07:55.839
So it's not only quicker, but it also freed up our hands. At least in our environment,

00:07:55.839 --> 00:07:59.279
we're limited to two workbenches, so it's kind of like having two R consoles or two

00:07:59.279 --> 00:08:03.279
tabs, and if I have many types of data that I need to process throughout a week, it's

00:08:03.279 --> 00:08:07.000
as if my hands are tied. So by being able to offload it off to a server, I can free

00:08:07.000 --> 00:08:13.079
up my hands to do other type of work. And we can schedule jobs on the server using,

00:08:13.079 --> 00:08:18.000
for example, the Officer or OpenXLSX package to make PowerPoints, Excel sheets, or Word

00:08:18.000 --> 00:08:24.760
documents. In that same data processing, we're going to also be doing the large amount

00:08:24.760 --> 00:08:29.480
of data processing and then creating reports that are output at a scheduled time. We can

00:08:29.480 --> 00:08:32.919
schedule e-mails with the Blasto package, and a couple e-mails here and there is not

00:08:32.919 --> 00:08:38.039
too bad, but when we start to initiate e-mails and data with a lot of different partners,

00:08:38.039 --> 00:08:43.520
this becomes a really great tool to use. And here's one example of data that we put on

00:08:43.520 --> 00:08:47.640
the website weekly for post-vaccination infection data if you want to check it out, and all

00:08:47.640 --> 00:08:51.159
of this data is processed via Connect and then shared with our partners at CDPH to

00:08:51.159 --> 00:08:55.919
later publish on the website. So you can kind of think of Connect as if they're replacing

00:08:55.919 --> 00:08:59.919
us. They're robots, they're running in their own lane, and they're running their own processes.

00:08:59.919 --> 00:09:02.960
And so at this point, I might want to sit back and look at my cat and listen to her

00:09:02.960 --> 00:09:08.039
and stop looking at this monitor, but in reality, automation isn't perfect and often actually

00:09:08.039 --> 00:09:13.000
fails and can be quite challenging to debug. Working on a server, the debugging process

00:09:13.000 --> 00:09:17.559
is a lot different. The logs are different. So we tried to, so we need to think about

00:09:17.559 --> 00:09:21.359
that as well. So in reality, it's more like this. We're all running in the same lane.

00:09:21.359 --> 00:09:27.000
Some of the processes are falling over, I'm falling over, et cetera. And one of the solutions

00:09:27.000 --> 00:09:32.679
to this was to create a data processing monitoring app. So this monitors all our processes on

00:09:32.679 --> 00:09:37.919
Connect, and it gives us a really great visualization of what's occurring and when it might fail.

00:09:37.919 --> 00:09:41.760
And in addition to that, we have an error logging system where if something breaks,

00:09:41.760 --> 00:09:47.559
we get an email via Blastula telling us something's broken and where in that script it broke.

00:09:47.559 --> 00:09:50.159
So I don't have time to share that with you right now, but if you're interested, there's

00:09:50.159 --> 00:09:53.679
actually a talk by my colleagues Colby Parrish and Andy Pham coming up next that you can

00:09:53.679 --> 00:09:57.880
check out to see that specific piece of our workflow.

00:09:57.880 --> 00:10:01.679
And then lastly, we have many different Shiny apps, mostly internal that I can't share with

00:10:01.679 --> 00:10:06.479
you, but one that was published to the public by the California COVID-19 modeling team called

00:10:06.479 --> 00:10:10.599
CalCat, and this shows you the current state and predicted future state using different

00:10:10.599 --> 00:10:15.200
models of COVID-19 in the state of California. So I encourage you to check this out and see

00:10:15.200 --> 00:10:18.440
the different types of data that we're working with, and what's, I think, really cool is

00:10:18.440 --> 00:10:21.840
that you can download the data as well that we've all been processing and that's updated

00:10:21.840 --> 00:10:24.840
regularly.

00:10:24.840 --> 00:10:28.599
So this gives you a very high-level overview of the different tools that we use to create

00:10:28.599 --> 00:10:33.479
this workflow using Azure DevOps, RStudio Workbench, and RStudio Connect, allowing us

00:10:33.479 --> 00:10:37.320
to process data in a very quick amount of time and freeing up our hands to make products

00:10:37.359 --> 00:10:41.840
that help guide decision-making in the state of where to allocate resources.

00:10:41.840 --> 00:10:45.039
So thank you all for your time, and special thanks to the data processing and informatics

00:10:45.039 --> 00:10:48.039
section for all of her work.

